                <h2>Letter X</h2>
                <p>The 'X' in ASL is formed by curling the index finger towards the thumb while extending the other
                    fingers out. The thumb is placed across the side of the index finger, creating a hook-like shape
                    that represents the letter 'X'.</p>
                <ul>
                    <li><strong>Initial Hand Position:</strong> Begin with your hand open, all fingers extended, and
                        palm facing forward.</li>
                    <li><strong>Curl Index Finger:</strong> Curl your index finger towards your palm, creating a
                        hook-like shape. The tip of the index finger should be pointing towards the thumb.</li>
                    <li><strong>Thumb Positioning:</strong> Place your thumb across the side of the curled index finger,
                        helping to maintain the hook shape.</li>
                    <li><strong>Extend Other Fingers:</strong> Keep your middle, ring, and pinky fingers extended
                        outward, away from the palm.</li>
                    <li><strong>Ensure Clarity:</strong> Ensure that the index finger is properly curled and the thumb
                        is correctly positioned to clearly form the letter 'X'. The hand should be steady, and the sign
                        held at eye level for visibility.</li>
                </ul>
                <p>Practice forming the 'X' sign to ensure its clarity and recognition. This letter has a unique shape
                    in the ASL alphabet and is essential for clear communication.</p>
